docs.text: drew barrymore is beginning to corner the market on playing the girl outside - the one who's the awkward klutz or the spunky do-it-yourselfer ; the one who just doesn't fit in with the others .

docs.text: the premise is simple .

docs.text: barrymore's josie geller , at 25 the youngest copy editor ever to be hired by the chicago sun-times , is assigned to go undercover and return to high school to do an expose on what today's teens are feeling and doing .

docs.text: josie ( she says she was named after the '70s cartoon character ) was a geek in high school , so she jumps at the opportunity for a second chance .

docs.text: this time , she thinks , she will get it right and be accepted by the in-crowd .

docs.text: now , what kind of adult - with a good job and a successful career - would actually look forward to reliving the hell that was - and is - high school and adolescence .

docs.text: screenwriters abby kohn and marc silverstein cannot get a handle of josie .

docs.text: their script has her capriciously switching from confident adult to ditzy , blubbering woman-child at the least provocation .

docs.text: and the fact that an adult would put so much stock into trying to become tight with the vapid airheads who are supposedly south glen high school's most popular girls leads you to question her maturity and mental stability .

docs.text: ok , so " never been kissed " is not a sociological expose of today's high school scene .

docs.text: however , certain rules should apply to film , and one of those is consistency of character .

docs.text: among the movie's problems is the ill-conceived conceit that josie would seriously strive to climb the high school food chain and , in the process , lose focus on her assignment .
